#compdef subjs
# ============================================================================
# subjs - extract JavaScript file URLs from
#          a list of subdomains / URLs
#          (Go, MIT)
#
# Author : Corben Leo (lc)
# Upstream: https://github.com/lc/subjs
#
# `subjs` is a Go CLI for automated extraction
# of JavaScript file URLs from a list of
# subdomains or URLs. Used heavily in
# authorized security testing workflows:
#   - Bug bounty reconnaissance (Hackerone +
#     Bugcrowd + Intigriti programs)
#   - Web application security audits of
#     own infrastructure
#   - CTF challenges involving web app
#     analysis
#   - JavaScript supply-chain audits (which
#     JS files does this application load
#     + from where + are any from
#     untrusted CDNs)
#
# Workflow:
#   1. Crawler (e.g. `gau` / `waybackurls`)
#      produces a list of URLs/subdomains
#   2. `subjs` fetches each URL + parses
#      the HTML
#   3. For each fetched HTML page, scrapes
#      <script src="..."> attribute values
#      via goquery's CSS selector engine
#   4. Outputs unique JavaScript file URLs
#      to stdout (one per line)
#   5. Downstream tools (e.g. `secretfinder`
#      / `linkfinder`) consume the JS URLs
#      for secret + endpoint extraction
#
# Distinguishing features vs alternatives:
#   - **Concurrent workers** (-c flag;
#     default 10 parallel HTTP fetchers
#     for fast scanning)
#   - **Stdin pipeline mode** (no input file
#     = read from stdin; suitable for
#     shell pipelines from gau/
#     waybackurls/subfinder/etc.)
#   - **Custom User-Agent** (-ua flag for
#     bypassing User-Agent-based WAF rules
#     or for tracking attribution)
#   - **Configurable timeout** (-t flag;
#     default 15 seconds for slow sites)
#   - **Single-file Go binary** (cross-
#     compiles to all platforms; no
#     runtime deps)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Bug bounty: discover all JavaScript
#     files loaded by a target's
#     subdomains (input from `gau` or
#     `waybackurls`)
#   - Security audit of own SaaS
#     application: enumerate JS supply
#     chain (which CDNs + which third-
#     party trackers load)
#   - CTF challenge: extract JS files for
#     secret discovery
#   - Web archive analysis: which JS files
#     did historical snapshots of a site
#     load (combine with Wayback Machine
#     URLs)
#
# Usage:
#   subjs [options]
#   cat urls.txt | subjs        # stdin
#
# Flags (Go stdlib flag):
#   -i <file>                      - input
#                                     file
#                                     containing
#                                     URLs
#                                     (one per
#                                     line)
#   -ua <string>                   - User-
#                                     Agent
#                                     to send
#                                     in HTTP
#                                     requests
#   -c <n>                         - number of
#                                     concurrent
#                                     workers
#                                     (default
#                                     10)
#   -t <n>                         - timeout
#                                     in
#                                     seconds
#                                     for HTTP
#                                     client
#                                     (default
#                                     15)
#   -version                       - show
#                                     version
#
# Example invocations:
#   # Read URLs from file + extract JS URLs
#   subjs -i urls.txt
#
#   # Pipeline from gau (Get All URLs)
#   gau example.com | subjs
#
#   # Pipeline from waybackurls
#   waybackurls example.com | subjs
#
#   # Pipeline from subfinder
#   subfinder -d example.com -silent | \
#     httpx -silent | subjs
#
#   # Custom User-Agent + 50 workers + 30s
#   # timeout
#   subjs -ua 'Mozilla/5.0 (security-audit)' \
#     -c 50 -t 30 -i urls.txt
#
#   # Full bug bounty pipeline
#   subfinder -d target.com -silent | \
#     httpx -silent | \
#     subjs -c 50 | \
#     sort -u > js-urls.txt
#
#   # Show version
#   subjs -version
#
# The PuerkitoBio/goquery lane is built on
# `github.com/PuerkitoBio/goquery v1.6.0`
# (declared verbatim at upstream go.mod HEAD
# as the project's sole non-stdlib dep,
# imported by `runner/subjs/runner.go` for
# parsing fetched HTML + extracting <script
# src="..."> attributes via CSS selectors),
# the canonical Go HTML scraping library by
# Martin Angers (PuerkitoBio) - github.com/
# PuerkitoBio/goquery.
#
# PuerkitoBio/goquery is the de-facto
# canonical Go HTML scraping library:
#   - **jQuery-style API** (the `$` /
#     Selection methods adapted to Go;
#     same API conventions as jQuery +
#     cheerio + scraper)
#   - **Built on golang.org/x/net/html**
#     (the official Go stdlib-extension
#     HTML5 parser; the same parser used
#     by goldmark + many Go HTML tools)
#   - **CSS selector support** (via the
#     andybalholm/cascadia CSS selector
#     library; the canonical Go CSS
#     selector matching engine)
#   - **Pure-Go implementation** (no CGO)
#   - **Document traversal API** (Find +
#     Filter + Each + Map + Children +
#     Parent + Siblings)
#   - **Manipulation API** (Append + Prepend
#     + Remove + ReplaceWith + Wrap +
#     Unwrap; for round-trip HTML
#     editing)
#   - **15,000+ stars on github.com/
#     PuerkitoBio/goquery**
#   - **~17,000 reverse-deps on
#     pkg.go.dev (one of the most-
#     imported Go libraries in the
#     web-scraping + HTML-processing
#     space)**
#
# PuerkitoBio/goquery's distinguishing
# position vs Go HTML scraping
# alternatives:
#   - PuerkitoBio/goquery (Angers):
#     canonical; jQuery-style API;
#     cascadia-backed; THIS AXIS
#   - golang.org/x/net/html: low-level
#     HTML5 parser (Go stdlib extension);
#     not a scraping API; goquery builds
#     on it
#   - andybalholm/cascadia: CSS selector
#     library (used by goquery);
#     standalone for non-goquery use
#     cases
#   - PuerkitoBio/fetchbot (also Angers):
#     polite + concurrent web crawler;
#     pairs with goquery for full
#     crawl-and-scrape pipelines
#
# Martin Angers (PuerkitoBio) is a long-time
# Go ecosystem contributor specializing in
# HTML + web crawling + parsing:
#   - **PuerkitoBio/goquery** (canonical
#     Go HTML scraping; THIS AXIS)
#   - **PuerkitoBio/fetchbot** (concurrent
#     web crawler; ~800 stars; pairs
#     with goquery)
#   - **PuerkitoBio/purell** (URL
#     normalization library; the Go
#     equivalent of RFC 3986 + RFC
#     3987 URL normalization rules)
#   - **PuerkitoBio/throttled** (HTTP
#     rate limiting middleware)
#   - **PuerkitoBio/martini-clean**
#     (pre-1.0 Go web framework
#     experiment)
#
# Angers's role in Go is *web crawling +
# HTML processing + URL handling
# infrastructure*. His library family
# forms a coordinated crawl-and-scrape
# stack (fetchbot for crawling + goquery
# for parsing + purell for URL
# normalization). Few canonical-Go
# authors maintain such a cohesive
# multi-library vertical stack.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Go author/org cohort
# extension (now spanning 25 distinct
# individuals/orgs after R1554):
#   - + Martin Angers (PuerkitoBio;
#     goquery + fetchbot + purell +
#     throttled; THIS AXIS; canonical
#     Go HTML scraping + web crawling
#     vertical stack)
#
# Angers joining the canonical-Go cohort
# at the *vertical-stack canonical
# author* level extends the pattern of
# *coordinated multi-library single-
# author* contributions documented
# across the corpus.
#
# Notable: the goquery + cheerio + scraper
# convergence on the jQuery-style API
# (documented in R1553 axis-opener
# header) is structurally distinctive.
# The jQuery $ + chained-method API
# became the de-facto pattern for HTML
# scraping across Rust + Go + Node
# despite all three being independent
# implementations with different
# underlying parsers (html5ever +
# golang.org/x/net/html + htmlparser2).
#
# jQuery's influence on HTML scraping
# API design is one of the strongest
# documented examples of cross-language
# API convention propagation in the
# corpus.
#
# subjs uses goquery for:
#   - Parsing each fetched HTML response
#   - Selecting all <script src="..."> +
#     <script type="..." src="..."> tags
#     via CSS selector `script[src]`
#   - Extracting the src attribute value
#     for each match
#   - Filtering for valid JS file URLs
#     (skipping inline scripts + data:
#     URLs)
#
# This is the canonical use case for
# goquery in production security tools:
# CSS-selector-based extraction of
# specific HTML attributes from large
# volumes of fetched pages.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 285 :: HTML parsing + scraping
#              libraries
#              (HTML5 spec-compliant
#              parsers + CSS selector
#              engines for web scraping +
#              full-text extraction + DOM
#              manipulation)
# Round 1554 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 285
#
# Cross-language canonical library family
# for this axis:
#   Rust    : causal-agent/scraper       [R1553 _feedr]
#             (Charles Edward Pax;
#              canonical Rust HTML
#              scraping; built on
#              Mozilla Servo html5ever +
#              selectors)
#   Go      : PuerkitoBio/goquery        [R1554 THIS FILE]
#             (Martin Angers; canonical
#              Go HTML scraping; jQuery-
#              style API; cascadia-
#              backed; 15,000+ stars)
#   TS/Node : cheeriojs/cheerio          [R1555 closing]
#             (Felix Böhm + maintainers;
#              canonical Node HTML
#              scraping; jQuery-style
#              API; the original)
#
# Use-case spectrum across the lanes (so far):
#   - feedr (Rust, scraper): RSS reader
#     full-text extraction pipeline
#     (parsing fetched article HTML for
#     main-content isolation)
#   - subjs (Go, goquery): bug bounty +
#     authorized security testing
#     JavaScript file URL extraction
#     from subdomain + URL lists
#
# Both use cases share the *CSS-selector-
# based HTML extraction* pattern - apply
# CSS selectors to fetched HTML +
# extract specific attribute values or
# inner content for downstream
# processing. This is the canonical
# scraping deployment pattern across
# production Rust + Go tooling.
# ============================================================================

_subjs() {
    _arguments \
        '-i+[input file containing URLs]:file:_files' \
        '-ua+[User-Agent to send in HTTP requests]:user-agent:' \
        '-c+[number of concurrent workers (default 10)]:n:' \
        '-t+[timeout in seconds for HTTP client (default 15)]:seconds:' \
        '-version[show version]'
}

_subjs "$@"
